(41, 3, 35, 40, 7, 21, 21, NULL, 'Connection of Doing God''s Will', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of doing the will of God or the Father. This connection highlights that true familial ties and entry into the kingdom are based on obedience to God''s will.', 'theme', 0.37, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 3, 35, 62, 3, 22, 23, 'do the will of God', 'Connection of Doing God''s Will', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of doing God''s will and keeping His commandments. Mark 3:35 highlights those who do God''s will as family, while 1 John 3:22-23 connects obedience to receiving from God and loving one another.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 3, 35, 43, 7, 17, 17, 'do the will of God', 'Connection of Doing God''s Will', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of doing the will of God. In Mark, doing God''s will establishes familial ties with Jesus, while in John, it leads to understanding His doctrine.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 3, 35, 59, 1, 25, 25, 'do the will of God', 'Connection of Doing God''s Will', 'This connection highlights the importance of being a ''doer'' of God''s will. Both passages emphasize that those who actively follow God''s commands are recognized as part of His family and will be blessed in their actions.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 1, 41, 2, 13, 13, 'by the sea side', 'Teaching by the Sea', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus teaching by the sea side, indicating a consistent setting for his ministry. The gathering of the multitude in both instances highlights the attraction of his teachings.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 1, 42, 5, 1, 3, 'by the sea', 'Teaching by the Sea', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus teaching from a boat by the water. In Mark, he teaches by the sea, while in Luke, he teaches from a ship at the lake. This connection highlights the setting of Jesus'' teaching ministry.', 'parallel', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 1, 42, 8, 4, 10, 'by the sea side', 'Teaching by the Sea', 'This connection highlights the setting of Jesus teaching by the sea, which is present in both passages. In Mark, he teaches by the sea side, while in Luke, he speaks to a gathered multitude, indicating a similar context for his parable.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 1, 40, 13, 1, 15, NULL, 'Teaching by the Sea', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus teaching by the sea, where great multitudes gathered to hear him. This setting serves as a backdrop for the parables he shares, illustrating the connection between the location and the message.', 'parallel', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 1, 41, 3, 7, 7, 'great multitude', 'Jesus Teaching by the Sea', 'Both passages emphasize a great multitude following Jesus by the sea. This connection highlights the significance of the sea as a setting for Jesus'' teaching and the gathering of people.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 2, 40, 13, 34, 35, 'taught them many things by parables', 'Teaching Through Parables', 'Both passages emphasize Jesus teaching in parables. Mark notes he taught ''many things by parables,'' while Matthew states he spoke ''without a parable spake he not unto them.'' This connection highlights the significance of parables in Jesus'' teaching method.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 2, 41, 3, 23, 23, 'taught them many things by parables', 'Teaching Through Parables', 'Both passages emphasize the use of parables in teaching. In Mark 4:2, Jesus teaches many things by parables, while in Mark 3:23, he uses a parable to question the logic of Satan casting out Satan.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 2, 41, 4, 11, 11, 'taught them many things by parables', 'Teaching Through Parables', 'This connection highlights the method of teaching used by Jesus. Both passages emphasize the use of parables to convey deeper truths about the kingdom of God.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 2, 19, 49, 4, 4, 'taught them many things by parables', 'Teaching Through Parables', 'Both passages emphasize the use of parables as a means of teaching. Mark 4:2 highlights Jesus teaching through parables, while Psalms 49:4 expresses a willingness to listen to a parable.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 2, 19, 78, 2, 2, 'by parables', 'Connection of Parables in Scripture', 'Both passages emphasize the use of parables as a teaching method. Mark 4:2 mentions teaching by parables, while Psalms 78:2 states, ''I will open my mouth in a parable.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 2, 40, 13, 3, 3, 'taught them many things by parables', 'Teaching Through Parables', 'Both passages emphasize the method of teaching through parables. Mark mentions Jesus teaching ''many things by parables,'' while Matthew introduces a specific parable about a sower.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 2, 43, 7, 16, 17, 'his doctrine', 'Connection of Doctrine in Teachings', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of ''doctrine'' as central to Jesus'' teachings. Mark highlights Jesus teaching through parables, while John clarifies that His doctrine is divinely sourced, suggesting a continuity in His message.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 3, 43, 4, 35, 38, 'sower to sow', 'Sowing and Reaping Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the process of sowing and reaping, illustrating the continuity of labor in God''s work. The sower in Mark initiates the process, while the reaper in John highlights the urgency of harvest, suggesting a shared mission in ministry.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 3, 46, 3, 6, 9, 'sower to sow', 'Sowing and Growth Connection', 'Both passages emphasize the act of planting and the subsequent growth that follows. The sower in Mark represents those who initiate the work, while 1 Corinthians highlights the collaborative effort in nurturing that leads to God''s increase.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 3, 59, 2, 5, 5, 'sower to sow', 'Connection of Sowing and Faith', 'This connection highlights the act of sowing as a metaphor for spreading faith, paralleling the idea of God choosing the poor who are rich in faith. Both passages emphasize the importance of receptivity to God''s message.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 3, 5, 4, 1, 1, 'Hearken', 'Call to Listen and Act', 'This connection highlights the imperative to ''hearken'' in both passages. In Mark, the sower''s act of sowing represents the dissemination of teachings, while in Deuteronomy, the call to listen emphasizes the importance of adhering to God''s statutes for life and possession of the land.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 3, 40, 13, 26, 26, 'sower to sow', 'Sowing and Growth Connection', 'This connection highlights the process of growth following the act of sowing. Both passages emphasize the outcome of the sower''s work, with Mark introducing the act of sowing and Matthew describing the subsequent growth and appearance of tares.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 3, 41, 4, 26, 29, 'sower to sow', 'Connection of Sowing and Growth', 'Both passages emphasize the process of sowing and the subsequent growth of seeds, illustrating the natural progression from planting to harvest. The imagery of a sower in Mark 4:3 connects directly to the description of seed growth in Mark 4:26-29.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 3, 42, 8, 5, 8, NULL, 'Connection of Sower Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the act of sowing, highlighting the sower''s journey and the varied outcomes of the seed. This connection illustrates the theme of receptivity to the message being shared.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 4, 40, 13, 19, 19, 'by the way side', 'Connection of Sowing and Understanding', 'Both passages emphasize the fate of the seed that falls by the way side. In Mark, it is devoured by fowls, while Matthew explains this as the wicked one catching away what was sown in the heart.', 'theme', 0.363, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 4, 41, 4, 15, 15, 'by the way side', 'Connection of Sowing and Reception', 'This connection highlights the imagery of sowing and the immediate response to the word. Both passages emphasize the fate of the seed that falls ''by the way side'' and the subsequent action of Satan in taking away the word.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 4, 40, 13, 4, 4, 'some fell by the way side', 'Connection of Sowing Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the act of sowing seeds and the immediate consequence of some seeds falling by the way side, leading to their consumption by fowls. This parallel highlights a shared narrative element in the teachings of Jesus.', 'parallel', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 4, 42, 8, 12, 12, 'by the way side', 'Connection of Sowing and Hearing', 'Both passages emphasize the fate of the seed that falls ''by the way side.'' Mark describes the seed being devoured, while Luke explains that the devil takes away the word from those who hear it. This connection highlights the vulnerability of those who do not fully receive the message.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 4, 1, 15, 11, 11, 'fowls of the air', 'Connection of Fowls in Scripture', 'This connection highlights the presence of fowls in both passages, where they play a role in consuming or disturbing what is sacred. In Mark, the fowls devour the seed, while in Genesis, Abram drives them away from the carcasses, suggesting a theme of protection against unwanted forces.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 4, 42, 8, 5, 5, 'some fell by the way side', 'Connection of Sowing Imagery', 'Both passages emphasize the act of sowing and the fate of the seed that falls by the way side, highlighting a common theme of the sower''s experience. The imagery of the fowls of the air devouring the seed is present in both texts, reinforcing the narrative of loss.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(41, 4, 5, 26, 36, 26, 26, 'stony ground', 'Stony Ground and Stony Heart', 'This connection highlights the theme of ''stony'' conditions in both passages. Mark describes seeds that fall on ''stony ground,'' while Ezekiel speaks of a ''stony heart'' that needs transformation.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
